File: The Sasol head office. AFP/Stephane De Sakutin JOHANNESBURG - Air Liquide’s plan to buy Sasol’s air-separation units has the go-ahead. The Competition Commission has recommended that the Tribunal approve the proposed transaction saying it's unlikely to prevent or reduce competition in the relevant markets. The acquisition is worth R8.5-billion. READ: Sasol plans retrenchments Its target assets are 16 air separation units based at the Sasol Secunda site, which produce mainly industrial gases. The plan is to reduce carbon emissions over 10 years, by at least 30 percent. Over and above the acquisition, Air Liquide will supply gases to the Sasol operation, under a 15-year agreement.